
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `crc32` yek code-e hash baraye file-ha ijad mikonad. In code baraye check kardane dorosti va taghir nakardane file-ha be kar miravad. Agar file taghir konad, code `crc32` avaz mishavad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `crc32 FILE`  --> 📄 Ijad code `crc32` baraye file morede nazar.  
    🔹 `crc32 < FILE`  --> 📤 Ijad code `crc32` az voroodi standard.  
    🔹 `crc32 -`  --> ⌨️ Az voroodi standard (keyboard) be عنوان file bekhavanad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ crc32 myfile.txt

    🔹 Ijad code `crc32` baraye file ba name "myfile.txt".

    $ cat myfile.txt | crc32

    🔹 Ijad code `crc32` az content file "myfile.txt".

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ crc32 hello.txt
    29637d7b

    🔹 Agar "hello.txt" taghir konad, code `crc32` fargh khahad kard. In be shoma komak mikonad ta مطمئن shavid file taghir nakarde ast.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `crc32` command generates a checksum (CRC32 code) for files. This code is used to verify the integrity of files and detect if they have been modified. If a file is changed, its CRC32 code will be different.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `crc32 FILE`  --> 📄 Generate the CRC32 code for the specified file.
    🔹 `crc32 < FILE`  --> 📤 Generate the CRC32 code from standard input.
    🔹 `crc32 -`  --> ⌨️ Read from standard input (keyboard) as a file.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ crc32 myfile.txt

    🔹 Generate the CRC32 code for the file named "myfile.txt".

    $ cat myfile.txt | crc32

    🔹 Generate the CRC32 code from the content of the file "myfile.txt".

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ crc32 hello.txt
    29637d7b

    🔹 If "hello.txt" is modified, the CRC32 code will change. This helps you ensure that the file hasn't been altered.
